					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-3090359#post-3606211</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-3090359/scp-2694#post-3606211</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 02 Oct 2017 18:23:59 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Communism will win</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>617958</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Less 'uncommon' and more 'archaic'. It's a 19th century sorta thing, and unless you're invoking an old-timey sorta feel, you should use 'spun' every time. I've personally never seen or heard 'span' used in real conversation.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-3090359#post-3606185</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-3090359/scp-2694#post-3606185</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 02 Oct 2017 17:38:29 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Scorpion451</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1918720</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>&quot;Span&quot; is uncommon but it's a valid past tense of spin.</p> <p>It's sort of like the shone/shined thing, where there are two valid forms and you'll see people argue for hours on which one is the &quot;correct&quot; one <sub>*cough*shone*cough*</sub> and which is the abomination unto language <sub>*cough*shined*cough*</sub>.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
